{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2066"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2066"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.1,0.08,0.47,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105505"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2066"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11568"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9991"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105505"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man is seen in the Emergency Department by the psychiatry liaison team. He is very unkempt and dishevelled. His family are concerned as he has not left his bed or eaten for many days. He has a previous diagnosis of major depressive disorder. The decision is made to trial electroconvulsive therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following, if present, would be a relative contraindication to the proposed treatment in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Previous history of epilepsy","Regular use of temazepam for insomnia","Previous stroke 12 months prior","Papilloedema seen on fundoscopy","Myocardial infarction 6 months prior"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are no absolute contraindications to ECT, however there are a number of relative contraindications.\u003Cbr /\u003EElectroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is a psychiatric treatment modality which uses an electric current to induce a generalised cerebral seizure. It is primarily used to treat patients with depressive disorders including major depression and major depression with psychotic features and major depression with peripartum onset. Other psychiatric disorders such as bipolar disorder (mixed, manic and depressed phases, acute and chronic treatment resistant schizophrenia, schizoaffective disorder, catatonia, acute psychosis, puerperal psychosis and neuroleptic malignant syndrome. ECT may have a stigma attached to it due to portrayal in the media and popular culture, although it is a relatively safe and low risk procedure, and may even have a safer profile than antidepressants or antipsychotics in debilitated, elderly, pregnant or breastfeeding patients. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe resultant seizure from ECT can cause a transient increase in blood pressure, myocardial oxygen demand, heart rate and intracranial pressure. For these reasons, relative contraindications to ECT include symptoms or signs of raised intracranial pressure (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epapilloedema\u003C/strong\u003E), a recent myocardial infarction (within past 3 months), severe hypertension, acute glaucoma, cardiovascular conduction defects, aortic and cerebral aneurysms, untreated hyperthyroidism, phaeochromocytoma and high-risk pregnancies. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EPrevious history of epilepsy is not a contraindication for ECT. There should be consideration of cessation of regular temazepam prior to ECT as it raises the seizure threshold, but it is not a contraindication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any evidence of raised intracranial pressure is a contraindication to electroconvulsive therapy."],"references":["Salik I, Marwaha R. Electroconvulsive Therapy. StatPearls. Treasure Island (FL)2020.","https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/0608270046ad5b01b893ba2195233e2a/Guideline_Electroconvulsive+Therapy_Dec2014.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026CACHE=NONE","https://www.ranzcp.org/files/resources/college_statements/practice_guidelines/ppg-administration-ect-electroconvulsive-therapy.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2066"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-09T16:33:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-09T16:33:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2066"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105505"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG